**Note:** The consistent 7 calls/step (across inter-spike and near-spike
regions alike) confirms that the current state is an excellent initial
guess for `fsolve` at dt = 0.01 ms, and the post-convergence reset
strategy successfully shields the root-finder from the discontinuity.

---

#### Complexity Analysis
| Complexity Type   | Class    | Reasoning                                                                 |
| :---              | :---     | :---                                                                      |
| **Time**          | O(N)     | N steps × O(1) fsolve calls (bounded iterations for fixed 2D system)     |
| **Space**         | O(N)     | Pre-allocated (N, 3) result array; no growing history buffer              |

- N = number of time steps = (T_END - T_START) / h
- fsolve overhead is a fixed constant multiplier (~7 function evaluations)
  regardless of N, so overall complexity remains linear.

---

#### Stability Note
The Backward Euler method is **A-stable** (unconditionally stable for
all step sizes h > 0), unlike RK4 which requires h < h_crit to avoid
blow-up. This is the primary advantage of the implicit formulation for
the stiff Izhikevich system.
